During the interview:
●  ●  ●  ●
1) Be enthusiastic and show interest/passion for testing. [Don't just say you want to be a Test Engineer because it's Google, relate your answer back to the role.] The interviewer(s) will be interested in the specifics of your past projects, implementations and how you arrived at your conclusions. The name of this game is Interaction!
2) Write very clean and structured code. We put a lot of emphasis on the quality of the code.
Start with the first solution that comes to mind; even if it’s slow at first - as long as the code solves the problem it will be good. [Start simple, you can build on it after]
You can implement a non-optimal solution and then work on it from there but the more optimal off the bat, the better.
Run a few examples to check the code and make sure you don’t assume that your code works. Make sure that your code works!
Check for edge cases.
Check for corner cases.
Try to implement null checks
Make sure there's no code repeatability, if so refactor it!
Make sure recursion terminates, no off by one errors, don’t plague your code.
Do not write pseudo code!
Try to use reasonable variable names to clean up the code (can use x or i).
Before you refine the code, ask if the interviewer if he has any questions about code
Try to be as efficient as possible with your implementation! [Don't over complicate your code]

3) Try to identify any bugs in your code and fix them along the way. [Assume someone else wrote the code and step it through line by line to look for bugs.]
4) Share your thought process with the interviewer! Think out loud so that they can follow you. [Talk to the interviewer to show you know how to approach the problem and find the constraints of the questions; shows you understand how to solve the problem]

Consider all the alternative solutions, and talk about the different ways you can do it.
Outline all possible approaches and weigh the different options.
5) Write as many test cases as possible. [Don't just give one or two, give as many as you can. Give test cases you expect to fail]
6) Ask clarifying questions.

Interview questions are underspecified to see what questions you will ask to clarify, so be sure to clarify the problem first. The reason you have to clarify is that you may think you are solving A but really the interviewer wants you to solve B.
Be sure to state and clarify key assumptions before diving into the code.
Also clarify the function signature; understand what’s coming in and what’s going out.
7) Take advantage of any hints they give you [Do not give up on a problem. Take the hints they give you no matter what.]

